Influence of marketing on term deposits subscriptions¶

The aim of this notebook is to analyse how the marketing campaign impact the inclination of customer to subscribe term deposit in his/her account. The dataset comes from UCI Machine Learning Repository and was derived from real data collected by Portuguese bank. The dataset consists of the following attributes:

  • Client personal information: age, job, marital status, education level
  • Previous client loans: if client has credit in default(default), housing loan(housing) or personal loan (loan)
  • Related with the campaign: contact communication type (contact), last contact month of year(month), last contact day of the week (day_of_week), last contact duration (duration), number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client(campaign), number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (pdays), number of contacts performed before this campaign (previous), outcome of the previous marketing campaign (poutcome)
  • Social and economic context attributes: quarterly indicator of employment variation rate (emp.var.rate), monthly indicator of consumer price index (cons.price.idx), consumer confidence index (cons.conf.idx), daily indicator of euribor 3 month rate (euribor3m), quarterly indicator of number of employees (nr.employed)

Dataset consists of 20 variables and one decision variable which is an information if client placed a term deposit or not. The aim of the following analysis will be to predict whether the client will place a term deposit or not. This will be achieved by classifying client's chance of deposit subscription on the basis of his/her personal information and the characteristics collected during conducted campaign. It should help bank decide, which clients should be included in next campaigns.

Cleaning and preprocessing data¶

General information¶

After looking at simple characteristics, I am already able to conclude that:

  • A lot of variables are not numerical variables, so dummy variables will have to be introduced
  • The amount of data for analysis is relatively big - it consists of 45307 observations
  • There is the same non-null count for every attribute, however it is not synonymous to lack of missing values, there still can be plenty of values that are not supposed to be attribute value.
  • There is uneven distribution of target variable in dataset. There is 40000 of observations where client didn't subscribe deposit and only approximately 5000 observations where target variable was positive.

Finding outliers¶

In this section I came to conclusion to remove variables:

  • duration
  • pdays
  • default

And transform values in:

  • age
  • campaign
  • education
  • job

Numeric variables¶

To find outliers, I've used statistic Z, with the assumption that every observation with z-score higher than 3 or smaller than -3 is an outlier. Obviously this doesn't need to be true, and the variables may not be outliers even if this assumption is met, however I need to use some measure to look into the matter.

The variables with outliers, according to this statistic, are:

  • age - but value of age shouldn't be considered as outlier, as we can see that minimal age in dataset is 17, while maximal 95. To minimize the impact of outliers, I will transform this variable logarithmically.
  • campaing - means number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client. Minimum value is 1 and maximal 43. To minimize the impact of outliers, I will transform this variable logarithmically.
  • pdays - it is the number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric; 999 means client was not previously contacted). The 999 value makes treating this variable as numerical a mistake. Moreover, we can see that most values of this variable is 999 (first quantile is already 999) which means that it can be at most transformed into binary variable saying if there was contact in the last campaign.
  • previous - which means number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client. Minimal is 0 and maximal 7. However, the third quantile is 0, which means that there is a small amount of cases in which the client was contacted previously. However as this variable seems important I will look into it in EDA.
  • duration - this variable will be also removed as highly affecting the output target. (e.g., if duration=0 then y='no').

Qualitative variables¶

I have already removed all "unknown" variables, but I will still check if there are any non-numerical variables, which are very undersampled, that is why I will join few categories in variables:

  • job
  • education
  • marital
  • variables loan, default and housing into one variable credit as they all mean different types of credits

There are also other variables that have too many labels, that are undersampled. However, later in the dataset there will be conducted Lasso Regression for feature selection which should deal with additional dummy variables.

# Joining categories

dataset['credit'] = dataset[['loan', 'housing', 'default']].apply(lambda x: x.str.contains('yes').any(), axis=1)
dataset['education'] = dataset['education'].replace(['basic.4y','basic.6y','basic.9y',"illiterate"],'basic')
dataset['education'] = dataset['education'].replace(['basic','high.school','professional.course'],'non-graduate')
dataset['job'] = dataset['job'].replace(['student','unemployed','retired'],'unemployed')
dataset['job'] = dataset['job'].replace(['self-unemployed', 'entrepreneur'],'self-employed')
dataset['job'] = dataset['job'].replace(['management','admin.'],'management and admin')
dataset['job'] = dataset['job'].replace(['blue-collar','services','management job'],'office')
dataset['job'] = dataset['job'].replace(['housemaid', 'services'], 'services' )
dataset['marital'] = dataset['marital'].replace(['divorced','married',],'married/divorced')
dataset.drop("loan", axis='columns', inplace=True)
dataset.drop("housing", axis='columns', inplace=True)
dataset.drop("default", axis='columns', inplace=True)

Exploratory data analysis¶

Due to EDA I made a conclusion that the most important features are:

  • emp.var.rate
  • euribor
  • nr.employed
  • previous

And some categories from:

  • job
  • education
  • contact
  • month
  • poutcome

Numeric variables¶

For most numeric variables, bars corresponding to true and false values of decisive attribute overlap each other. It means that these variables alone have little predictive power to classifiy if the client will subscribe deposit or not. The bars corresponding to no-subscription are higher than the other ones however it only says that there is more observations with this value with term deposit subscription.

In [19]:
sns.pairplot(dataset, kind="scatter", hue = "y", palette="bright" )
Out[19]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x20abdc5f9a0>

More information can be obtained from correlation matrix. There are some attributes highly correlated with each other:

  • correlations of three variables - emp.var.rate, nr.employed, euribor3m (corr>0.9) with each other and their reverse correlation with previous (corr < -0.4). They are all economic context attributes, so their correlations is understandable. Previous means number of contacts performed before this campaign, so the correlation is probably random and not the consequence of any causality.

High correlation between euribor3m,emp.var.rate and nr.employed cannot be ignored. However mostly classification models are able to deal with correlations if they are not perfect. Anyway during building models I will use feature selection in models, so the negative impact on prediction shouldn't occure.

There is also visible, which numerical variables have the highest correlation with predicted variable:

  • emp.var.rate so quarterly indicator of employment variation rate
  • euribor3M so daily indicator of euribor 3 month rate
  • nr.employed which means quarterly indicator of number of employees
  • previous which means number of contacts performed before this campaign

It means that these variables should have the greatest impact on success of prediction.

Qualitative variables¶

  • Job - I can make conclusion that there is visibly more chance for deposit subscription if clients are unemployed (students, retired or unemployed). The percentage of deposit subscriptions is high in these groups (between 20% and 30%).

  • Marital status - There is slightly more single people that made deposit.

  • Education - Clients with university degree have a little more percentage of open deposits than other group.

  • Contact - People who were contacted by cellular have put deposits more often

  • Month and day - this may be surprising but people who were contacted in December, March, October and September placed deposits more often. However, there is no visible connection with target class when it comes to day variable.

  • Poutcome - if the previous campaign was success, there is higher chance of deposit subscription. Also, if there was failure of a previous campaign, the chance of positive deposit subscription is higher than if there was no campaign at all.

Dimensionality reduction¶

PCA¶

After introducing dummy variables dataset has 33 columns. This is why I will use Principle Component Analysis and try to select features that are responsible for 90% of variance. This is reducing number of columns to 21 explaining 90% of variance.

Number of components explaining 90% of variance:  21

Taking into consideration the table below I can conclude:

  • for first component most important features are emp.var.rate, cons.price.idx, euribor3m and nr. employed so the variables that on the basis of correlation matrix were strongly correlated with each other and had great impact on target variable. This component also explains most of the variance - 15%
  • For the second component, the most important feature is job office and month may. This component explains 6.5% of variance.
  • For the third component cons.conf.index, age and month September are the most important features. This component explains 5.7 % of variance.

Other components can be analyzed similarly. However, it is visible that many components explain only a small percentage of variance (2% - 3%). This means that dataset consist of many variables, but most of them has only small impact on target.

Feature selection¶

As dataset has a lot of variables, even though explanatory data analysis gave me some insight into which variables should be more and which less beneficial for the prediction I decided to use algorithmic feature selection method rather than remove them one by one myself. After conducting Lasso Regression for Feature Selection method to evaluate variables according to their importance, the dataset consists of 14 variables. We can see that variables, that weren't removed, are mostly the ones that in the previous few sections were discovered as the ones with most causation of target variable.

In [27]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import RobustScaler, StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso

scaler = RobustScaler()
X = dataset.drop("y", axis='columns', inplace=False)
y = dataset['y']
X_scaled = scaler.fit(X).transform(X)
X_scaled

lasso = Lasso(alpha=0.002)
lasso.fit(X_scaled, y)
FI_lasso = pd.DataFrame({"Feature Importance": lasso.coef_}, index=X.columns)
keep_values = []
for x in FI_lasso.sort_values("Feature Importance", ascending=False):
    if x == True:
        keep_values.append(x)

X = X[FI_lasso[FI_lasso.values != 0].index]

Classification¶

First, I have divided the dataset into 80% train set and 20% test set. Then I have divided train set again into 80% train and 20% validation set.

For the classification, I chose 3 classifiers:

  • LogisticRegression
  • DecisionTree
  • XGBoost

Models are tuned used cross validators and parameter optimization. Moreover, to validate classifiers I will use AUC metric. I cannot use accuracy, because the positive class was strongly undersampled in the dataset.

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix


def plot_confusion_matrix(cm,
                          classes,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=90)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j,
                 i,
                 format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.ylabel('True values')
    plt.xlabel('Received values')
    plt.tight_layout()

Logistic Regression¶

The first algorithm used for classification was Logistic Regression. The weights had to be actualized for imbalanced data. I will also use L2 Regularization, so the model will not increase its complexity too much. The features will be selected by Recursive Feature Selection, so searching for a subset of features by starting with all features in the training set.

The overall classification score for validation data was:

  • Accuracy from LogisticRegression: 83%
  • Recall from LogisticRegression: 61%
  • AUC from LogisticRegression: 74%

Decision Tree¶

The second algorithm used for classification was Decision Tree checked for two splitting criteria and various maximal tree depths, number of min samples in leaf and split. The overall classification score for validation data was:

  • Accuracy from DecisionTree: 82%
  • Recall from DecisionTree: 63%
  • AUC from DecisionTree: 74%

Results¶

To sum up the bests results that I was able to obtain during validation was 84% accuracy (XGBoost), 74% AUC (all models), 63% Recall(Decision Tree). Apart from small differences all models performed similarly. Overfitting wasn't observed during training. The scores during training were almost the same as during validation for all models.

The most important in this kind of problem is to found out as many positive cases of target variable as possible. It is more costly for a bank to accidentally omit a client who could probably make a deposit than include him/her in the future campaign even if it may not be 100% surely successful. However, recall(sensitivity), so measure that is the proportion of positives that are correctly identified shouldn't be used as the main metrics during training the model (roc_auc was used), because it would pose a threat of classifying all negative cases as positive. Nonetheless, as the best classifier I will use Decision Tree because it returned the highest Recall. I don't pay much attention to accuracy score, because it is not really informative when the dataset is imbalanced.

The obtained results for test set decreased in comparision to validation.

  • Accuracy - 81%

This score means that in overall, 81% of test clients were assigned to the right class.

  • Recall for Test Set: - 60%

This score means that in overall, 60% of test clients who are truly a positive class were assigned to positive class.

  • AUC for Test Set - 72%

An area of 1 represents a perfect test, while an area of 0.5 represents a worthless test. AUC equal to 0.72 is acceptable, but not excellent.

ROC curve shows trade-off between sensitivity (or TPR) and specificity. According to the ROC curve, the conclusion can be made that to have 0.6 true positive rate, the classifier has to also have more than 20% of false positive rate. To have 90% of true positive rate, classifier would have to score around 90% false positive rates, so practically classify every client as positive.

Precision-Recall curve is a useful measure of success of prediction when the classes are very imbalanced. The precision-recall curve shows the trade-off between precision and recall for different threshold. A precision-recall curve helps to visualize how the choice of threshold (minimum probability to assign object to positive class) affects classifier performance.

No skill mean is a line that equals to the number of percent positive cases in a dataset. In this case it was something around 15%. It means that random classifier will predict positive case with this probability. Compared to that, obtained model is doing a better job, but far from perfect. The curve shows that to have 0.6 precision (ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the total predicted positive observations) the recall(percent of positive cases properly classified) could be only 0.2, so most predicted positive cases would have to be false positives.

The model used for classification had 0.60 recall and 0.4 precision, because I wanted to maximize recall as good as I could, even if this will lead to more false positives.

Summary¶

The main encountered problem in the above analysis was the imbalanced distribution of target cases and the huge dataset with a lot of variables but each having only small impact on the target variable. I have managed to obtain 60% success of correctly predicted positive observations in dataset, which mean that in average 60% of clients who will subscribe a deposit will be discovered by final model and 81% overall success in assigning right class for target variable. This score could be probably higher if training of models was only concentrated on sensitivity and not on the AUC score, however then performance of the model at distinguishing between the positive and negative classes would be lower, and it could lead to extreme case where each client would be assigned with positive case. Maybe predictions would be better if more data transformations would be conducted before classifications. The another problem was that due to great amount of data it was hard to tune parameters of more powerful model (xgboost), as tuning took a lot of time. Probably it might have been beneficial to remove more variables before starting classification.
